Chapter 1: The Zero-Bit Ghost
The air in the Aethelgard Academy's lower maintenance levels was thick with the smell of ozone and burnt copper. In a world powered by Essence, even the lightbulbs were "Smart Scripts"—tiny fragments of Void-code that provided illumination.
Ren sat on a cold concrete floor, a mechanical soldering iron in his hand. He wasn't using magic to fix the flickering conduit in front of him. He was using solder and wire.
[System Warning: Environmental Essence Level – Low]
[User Status: Unregistered (Zero-Bit)]
Ren ignored the translucent red box flickering at the edge of his vision. To the rest of the world, that box was a death sentence. In Aethelgard, if the System couldn't "see" you, you didn't exist. You couldn't buy food at the automated kiosks, you couldn't open the pressurized dorm doors, and you certainly couldn't cast a Level 1 Spark.
"Still playing with trash, Ren?"
The voice belonged to Jax, a Tier-2 "Bruiser" student whose uniform was always perfectly pressed. He stood in the doorway, his skin glowing with a faint, healthy amber hue—the sign of active Essence circulation.
"The conduit was arcing," Ren said without looking up. "If the physical copper melts, your 'Smart Script' won't have a medium to travel through. The whole wing would go dark."
Jax laughed, the sound echoing off the damp walls. "That’s what we have Tier-1 Technicians for. But you... you’re not even a Tech. You’re just a ghost. A Zero. Why the Academy keeps you around to sweep floors is the biggest mystery in the city."
Jax snapped his fingers. A small spark of amber energy danced between his knuckles. It was a simple display of power, but to Ren, it felt like a weighted blanket pressing against his chest. Because Ren had 0.00% Affinity, his body didn't have a "filter." Raw Essence felt like radiation to him—nauseating and cold.
"Warden Vane wants the loading docks cleared by 0600," Jax said, his eyes narrowing. "Move it, Ghost. The real students have a field trip to Site 9 today. We don't want to see you clogging up the halls."
Jax kicked Ren’s toolbox, spilling the carefully organized copper shims across the floor, and swaggered out.
Ren waited until the footsteps faded before he exhaled. His lungs burned. He reached into his pocket and pulled out a small, blackened metal disc he’d found in the scrap heaps of the South Gate. It was dead weight—no Essence, no glow—but it had a strange, jagged texture that felt familiar.
Suddenly, the red warning box in his vision flickered. It didn't disappear; it distorted.
[System Error: Unknown Hardware Detected]
[Analyzing... 0%...]
Ren froze. The disc in his hand grew ice-cold.
"Not now," he whispered, glancing at the security camera in the corner. If the Academy's "Antivirus" drones detected a logic error in his sector, they’d purge the room with a localized vacuum.
[Analysis Complete: Administrator 'Legacy' Key identified.]
[Status: User 'Ren' granted 'Observer' Permissions.]
[Warning: Your physical hardware (Body) is insufficient to run 'Admin.exe'.]
The world didn't turn into a power fantasy. It turned into a headache.
Ren’s vision fractured. The wall in front of him was no longer just concrete. He saw a scrolling list of Metadata.
 * Material: Reinforced Aggregate (88% Integrity)
 * Stress Point: 4.2cm behind the conduit.
 * Active Script: 'Luminescence_v4' (Status: Corrupted/Arcing)
He wasn't stronger. He was just seeing the "bugs" in the world's code.
A heavy thud vibrated through the floorboards. Then a scream—high, sharp, and cut off abruptly—echoed from the loading docks above.
[Event Detected: Perimeter Breach at Site 9]
[Logic Error: The 'Veil' has been manually set to 'Transparent'.]
Ren stood up, his heart hammering against his ribs. Site 9 wasn't just a ruins site; it was where the Academy stored its "trash"—the failed experiments and the corrupted Void-shards.
If the Veil was transparent, the "trash" was coming out. And Ren, the boy who didn't exist in the system, was the only one who could see the "Delete" button.

Narrative Causality Check:
 * The Power: Ren isn't "strong." He has Observer Permissions. He sees the weaknesses of objects and scripts, but he still has to use his physical body to act on them.
 * The Conflict: He’s physically nauseated by Essence, making him vulnerable to every other student.
 * The Hook: Someone manually turned off the safety shields at Site 9.
